  <Fragment slot="headline">How Much Are Tariffs Costing You in 2026? A Household Breakdown</Fragment>

  <p>If you've noticed your grocery bill creeping up, your new car costing more than expected, or your Amazon orders hitting a little harder — tariffs are a big reason why.</p>
  <p>In 2026, the average American household is paying somewhere between <strong>$600 and $1,800 extra per year</strong> due to import tariffs, depending on which estimates you look at and which tariffs remain in effect. That's $50 to $150 per month that wasn't in your budget before.</p>
  <p>This guide breaks down where that money is going, which products are hit hardest, and how to estimate the impact on your specific household.</p>

  <hr />

  <h2>The Numbers: What Experts Say</h2>
  <p>Multiple nonpartisan research organizations have estimated the household cost of tariffs in 2026. The numbers vary because tariff policy has been changing rapidly, especially after the Supreme Court struck down IEEPA tariffs in February 2026.</p>
  <p>The <strong>Tax Foundation</strong> estimates the average household burden at roughly <strong>$600 to $1,000</strong> in 2026, accounting for the Section 232 tariffs on steel, aluminum, autos, and lumber, plus the temporary 10% Section 122 tariff.</p>
  <p>The <strong>Yale Budget Lab</strong> calculated an average household loss of approximately <strong>$1,751</strong> in 2025 dollars before consumers shift their buying habits, dropping to about <strong>$1,292</strong> after substitution effects.</p>
  <p>The <strong>Tax Policy Center</strong> puts the figure at about <strong>$1,230</strong> per household for 2026, noting that the bottom 20% of earners are hit proportionally harder than the top 20%.</p>
  <p>The common thread: tariffs act as a hidden tax that gets passed through to consumers via higher prices.</p>

  <hr />

  <h2>Which Products Cost More?</h2>
  <p>Not everything is affected equally. Here's where you'll feel it most.</p>

  <h3>Cars and auto parts — the biggest single hit</h3>
  <p>The 25% tariff on imported vehicles remains in effect. Car prices have risen roughly 13.5% on average, adding about <strong>$6,400</strong> to the price of a new car. Even domestically assembled cars are more expensive because their supply chains depend on imported parts from Canada, Mexico, and Asia.</p>

  <h3>Clothing and shoes</h3>
  <p>Apparel faces tariff rates of 15–25% depending on the country of origin. A toddler clothing set from Southeast Asia that cost $24 might now cost $30–36. Jeans, sneakers, and fast fashion are all affected.</p>

  <h3>Electronics and appliances</h3>
  <p>Smartphones, laptops, and home appliances have seen modest price increases. While some tech products received exemptions, components like semiconductors and circuit boards still face tariffs that ripple through to final product prices.</p>

  <h3>Groceries and food</h3>
  <p>About 60% of fresh fruit consumed in the US is imported. Coffee, chocolate, olive oil, and seafood are all subject to tariffs. The impact here is smaller per item but adds up across a monthly grocery bill.</p>

  <h3>Home goods and furniture</h3>
  <p>Furniture, tools, and building materials (especially lumber and steel) have been directly targeted. If you're renovating or building, expect 10–25% higher material costs.</p>

  <AdSlot slot="mid" format="horizontal" />

  <hr />

  <h2>Who Gets Hit Hardest?</h2>
  <p>Tariffs are regressive — meaning lower-income households pay a larger share of their income toward tariff-related price increases.</p>
  <p>The Tax Policy Center found that the bottom 20% of earners see their effective tax rate rise by <strong>1.1 percentage points</strong>, while the top 20% see only a <strong>0.9 percentage point</strong> increase. In dollar terms, wealthier households pay more total, but it's a smaller slice of their budget.</p>
  <p>This happens because lower-income households spend a larger proportion of their income on physical goods (food, clothing, household items) rather than services, and physical goods are what tariffs directly affect.</p>

  <hr />

  <h2>How to Estimate Your Tariff Cost</h2>
  <p>Here's a rough way to estimate how much tariffs are costing your household.</p>

  <h3>Step 1: Start with your annual household spending on goods</h3>
  <p>The baseline estimate is about <strong>2.3% of household spending</strong> going to tariff-related price increases (Yale Budget Lab estimate at peak tariff levels). With current, post-Supreme Court tariff levels, it's closer to <strong>0.8–1.3%</strong>.</p>

  <h3>Step 2: Calculate your approximate extra cost</h3>
  <p>Take your annual household spending on goods (not services like rent, healthcare, or utilities) and multiply by the tariff impact percentage.</p>

