  <hr />

  <h2>What Changed After the Supreme Court Ruling?</h2>
  <p>On February 20, 2026, the Supreme Court ruled 6-3 that the President cannot impose tariffs under the International Emergency Economic Powers Act (IEEPA). This struck down the bulk of the tariffs that had been in place since 2025.</p>
  <p>However, the administration responded quickly with alternative tariffs. A new 10% tariff on most imports was imposed under Section 122, and existing Section 232 tariffs on steel, aluminum, vehicles, and lumber remain in effect. Several new Section 301 investigations are also underway targeting manufacturing sectors in over 15 countries.</p>
  <p>The bottom line: tariffs are lower than their 2025 peak, but they haven't gone away. The current average effective tariff rate sits at roughly <strong>12%</strong> — still the highest in decades.</p>

  <AdSlot slot="mid2" format="rectangle" />

  <hr />

  <h2>Ways to Reduce Your Tariff Exposure</h2>
  <p>You can't avoid tariffs entirely, but you can minimize their impact on your budget.</p>

  <p><strong>Buy domestic when the price difference is small.</strong> For some products, domestically made alternatives are now price-competitive with tariffed imports. This is especially true for basic groceries and some household goods.</p>
  <p><strong>Time major purchases carefully.</strong> Tariff rates and exemptions change frequently. If you're planning to buy a car or major appliance, check whether any temporary exemptions are in effect.</p>
  <p><strong>Comparison shop more aggressively.</strong> Different retailers absorb tariff costs differently. Some pass through 100% to consumers; others eat part of the cost to stay competitive.</p>
  <p><strong>Consider used or refurbished products.</strong> Tariffs apply to new imports, not secondhand goods. For electronics and vehicles, the used market has become significantly more attractive.</p>

